>all) POs in Indulgences executed up to this point, and I strenuously dispute
>all such POs. The existence of CFJ 937 should be sufficient, its content is
>irrelevant.

It was clear from your comments that your intention was to dispute the legality
of Indulgence POs.  The question was, did your CFJ actually do that.  The
contents of the CFJ are hardly irrelevant to making that determination and I
would be remiss in my duties if I were to ignore the contents.  The mere
existence of a CFJ is not enough to dispute anything.  Contents are all.

>> If a True verdict would definitely invalidate the Indulgence POs (or a False
>> verdict for that matter), then I would be inclined to say, yes, the POs are
>> in dispute.

>It seems to me that you are applying a double standard here. You assert that a
>Judge's reasoning becomes part and parcel of Game Custom if unchallenged, and
>in one specific instance, Vlad's Judgement, you are prepared to draw
>conclusions from a Judge's reasoning that reach far beyond the scope of the
>actual Statement and its truth or falsity, ...

I think a Judges reasoning in an unchallenged verdict should carry much more
weight than a Caller's reasoning in eir arguments.  Personally, I don't think a
caller's argument should carry any weight wrt game custom until accepted by the
Judicial process.  Of course, I think the caller's arguments should be given
all due respect and consideration by Judges.  From my point of view, I have not
applied a double standard here.

>...yet you claim that since a
>Judgement of either TRUE or FALSE in 937 would not necessarily lead to
>conclusions as to the validity of Indulgence POs 937 does not challenge these
>POs. What if the Judge's reasoning in 937 did state that POs were invalid,
>then ? You would have to turn around and state that 937 did challenge such
>POs, wouldn't you ?

Let me answer the last question first.  I would not say that CFJ 937 challenged
the validity of POs given your hypothetical.  I would say that the Judge's
reasoning, if accepted into game custom, invalidated them.  It would be fair to
say that your CFJ then *indirectly* challenged the validity of Indulgence POs. 
I interpret the PO dispute Rule to mean a CFJ that directly challenges the
validity of a PO.

Here's the way I see the current situation.  CFJ 937 was really the antecedent
to a *possible* challenge of Indulgence POs.  If judged True, then it *might*
be true that Indulgence POs were invalid.  In the absence of reasoning by the
Judge of 937 wrt to that validity (shortcutting the disputation of those POs),
it would require another CFJ to establish that fact.  The second CFJ is the one
I would consider to have brought Indulgence POs into dispute.  OTOH, if you had
made the second CFJ directly challenging the validity of Blot POs first, and
used the statement of 937 as caller's arguments, *then* I would have
automatically considered Induglence POs to be in dispute.  And we would not be
having this interesting discussion.  8)

